 A little bit about the childhood, maybe about the school days, and then the beginning of your career.

101
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:08,000
 And let's try to go to this point in bite-size stories, maybe, or something like that.

102
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 Sure.

103
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,000
 That's going really way back.

104
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 I usually go back 10 years and that's about it.

105
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 Okay.

106
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:16,000
 Born Toronto, Canada.

107
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 So, I was born in Canada and I was there until I finished elementary school.

108
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 Both parents are Croatian, so at one point they decided to move to Croatia to Split.

109
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 And I moved here in high school and been, so moved to Split Croatia in high school and been there ever since.

110
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:41,000
 Although I've traveled all over the place, but basically been living there for quite some time.

111
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 So, what was the experience of coming back to Croatia when you were a teenager already?

112
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 Were you speaking with your parents, Croatian, or?

113
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:58,000
 Yeah, I had, our parents made us go to Croatian school on Saturdays, so I had six days of school as a kid.

114
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 So, Monday to Friday, normal school, and then Saturday, Croatian school.

115
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 I hated them because of that, because I couldn't watch cartoons.

116
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
 Because there's always, all the best cartoons were Saturday mornings.

117
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 Oh my God.

118
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 Yeah.

119
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 And were you talking Croatian in house with the parents?

120
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 So, I say, like the way we spoke, I would say it was Anglo-Croatian.

121
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 Anglo-Croatian.

122
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:25,000
 Over there, but when we moved to Croatia, it became Croatian English or whatever.

123
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 In the sense that we'd use more, in Canada we used more English words and then threw Croatian in it.

124
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 And when we came here, it was vice versa.

125
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 So, just for example, we would always use, I don't even know what the word for sink, so sink in the kitchen is.

126
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:44,000
 And we'd use a Croatian sentence and say we left it in the sink.

127
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 But like everything else would be Croatian, but the sink would stay in English.

128
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 So, that's the kind of quasi-language we used at home.

129
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,000
 Okay.

130
00:05:50,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 I think that people in this region are more familiar with German, Croatian, gastrobatical, that kind of accent, but this one is also famous and popular.

131
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 So, maybe before we go to the start of your entrepreneurial career, which is maybe the focus of this episode.

132
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 Can you maybe give us an idea of, do you think that your childhood and the parenting style of your parents has something to do with the situation that you are in right now, that helped you in some ways?

133
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 Sure.

134
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 I mean, for one thing, as a child, I was by trilingual, I think, in that sense.

135
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:55,000
 I sort of forgot French, but we went, half the day was in French by choice, not by, it wasn't, you didn't have to.

136
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 It was mandatory.

137
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 Yeah, it wasn't mandatory, but you could do it.

138
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 We did French half the day, English half the day, and then Croatian Saturday.

139
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 So, that helps you sort of like, your mind, I guess, learns sort of to learn things.

140
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 And on top of that, even when we're talking about here in this part of the world, in this region of the world, I see that a lot of people that are entrepreneurial have actually lived a lot abroad or are originally from abroad.

141
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:37,000
 I mean, there are people that haven't done both, but a large proportion are, and I think that's something to do with the general upbringing of that Western type of thought, as that, you know, you can do whatever you want.

142
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 Like, you're the master of your own destiny.

143
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 Not to say that everyone does that.

144
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:46,000
 I mean, there's all sorts of people everywhere in the world, both rich and poor, successful and unsuccessful.

145
00:07:46,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 But just coming from a place where everyone tells you can, and you believe you can, and then you come to a place where a lot of people think you can't, I think that does maybe push you to actually do that, because you're very rarely, very often, you're the only one in the room that actually believes that.

146
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 So, I think that's something that pushes you in that direction.

147
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 I've never been to Canada before, I've been to United States. In a few simple words, could you describe or maybe compare the mindset of Canadians when you compare it with American ones?

148
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 Because when you say that living abroad gives you the opportunity, maybe that you have this bigger belief in yourself and that you can achieve bigger goals, especially when you're thinking about America, it is inside of the DNA of their culture that everything is possible.

149
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,000
 When you compare it with the Canadians?

150
00:08:49,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 Canadians are less so. I'd say, like, Canada is the nice brother of the US. So, Canadians are very polite. They're very, like, thank you, and they'll ask you how you're doing and whatnot.

151
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 So, they're very, very, very polite. And, but they're not as, in general, when you take them, like, everything that the United States of America has, for the good and the bad, all the extremes, I mean, for the good and bad, you have it in Canada, but not as extreme.

152
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 So, you don't have people as successful. I mean, in general, the number one place for billionaires in the world, I think, still is the United States of America.

153
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 So, like, you have that, but you also have less of the extreme on the other side.

154
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 So, it's more of a perfect or more of a nice place. So, it sits somewhere in between the extremes of, like, highly successful and highly unsuccessful people.

155
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:49,000
 So, you get a lot of that from the US, a lot of influence, but a lot more safe, nice, I think.

156
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 Yeah. Okay. So, let's, let's unveil your entrepreneurial story.

157
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 As from what I could research, the beginning, was it with code anywhere or was something before the code anywhere?

158
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 We had, I had two things before. So, the first thing that we can call entrepreneurial, I think, in that sense, I created a, with my younger brother,

159
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 a search engine for RapidShare. RapidShare was something that people used before Torrents, anyway.

160
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:33,000
 There's legit use cases for that, and I won't go into details other than that, but I created that search engine,

161
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 and it was just a hack together job and used some SEO tactics and ended up getting a Google Ads check every month in the mail.

162
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 And I was fairly young. I was still in high school or university, I think it was high school.

163
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 And making, so that was sort of the first project I made, and I ended up selling it to a person.

164
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 So, I actually got acquired. A guy out of Istanbul sent me an email, went back and forth.

165
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:06,000
 We ended up selling it. I mean, I sold it for $5,000, but it was like, yeah, I made $5,000, great.

166
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 So, that was my first exit. After that, I, at some point, I got a job as a system administrator in a fairly large company.

167
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:23,000
 So, it was a couple hundred people. Sort of moved through the ranks, became the leader of the sort of IT department,

168
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:29,000
 and spin that out into my own company. So, it was basically a system integrator company.

169
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 A company that does anything from software integrations to hardware, servers, routers, and that sort of thing.

170
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 Very old IT in that sense. While I had that, I actually met the co-founder of Code Anywhere, which we started.

171
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:53,000
 I can get into that later. But I figured that the way the market was going, the margins were, I decided that there wasn't enough potential in that old IT.

172
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 And then I sold that to a competitor, local competitor. So, that was my sort of like second exit, which was a couple of times.

173
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:04,000
 It was quite.

174
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 So, you were talking about the Code Anywhere?

175
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 No, no, no. Before that. It was a company, it was a company before that. So, I had a first company, it was called Gapon, which is a search engine.

176
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:11,000
 Okay.

177
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 Then I had a company called Procedo, which is the IT service company.

178
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:16,000
 Okay.

179
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 And I sold that to a competitor locally. And then I had Code Anywhere. Yeah. And so, while I was doing Code Anywhere, I also started the conference, which later got acquired.

180
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:31,000
 But Code Anywhere was an interesting one. If you've watched HBO's Silicon Valley, the show.

181
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 Yes.

182
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 So, like the whole first season was our life, 2014, '13, something like that. So, we went to San Francisco. We were on the stage at TechCrunch and Strap.

183
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 We got the investors. We went to Techstars. We got the checks on coffee with people. So, we went to an investor on coffee and we went home with a $50,000 check, right?

184
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 And we did that all the way up until almost a million dollars that we got into that, which was not super big at the time, but fairly decent.

185
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 For Code Anywhere.

186
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:10,000
 For Code Anywhere, yeah. So, that company went, the company's fairly old. It was incorporated in 2013 and now it's 2022. So, nine years, although we did it before a couple years as well.

187
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:22,000
 So, it's almost a teenager of a company for a startup that is old and it's had its ups and downs. And right now, it's actually going very, very well.

188
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 The idea behind that is, as you said, it's a Google Docs for software developers. So, software developers can, inside their web browser, program code and collaborate, see each other's cursors and stuff like that.

189
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 It was always made as an end user product, meaning similar to Google Docs, you, yourself personally and me will go to the website, create account and use it.

190
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 But what we have moved into the last sort of year is business to business, where we actually give the software to other companies to embed into their own software.

191
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:57,000
 And that has been actually going very well as of late. So, should I pause here for a second? I feel like I've been talking too much.

192
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 No, it's fine. So, I see that you are the real definition of the serial entrepreneur.

193
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:09,000
 Just the next one, yeah.

194
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 Just the next one.

195
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 I think it's more, sorry to jump in. So, I think it's more as I have, I don't want to be a serial entrepreneur.

196
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 I believe it's a means to an end in the sense that a lot of people want to be the next Bezos, Elon Musk, whatever.

197
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 Like you have, you're successful in what you do in that one thing.

198
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 And I do believe that's the best way.

199
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 But I, but being a person living in like the outskirts of the second largest city, I mean the largest city of a four million person country, without the financial background knowledge or like I had no idea what the hell I was doing.

200
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:53,000
 Without that, I felt like these were the, this is what I knew and I used that to create a company.

201
